WEBVTT

00:02.086 --> 00:05.171
♪♪ [Orchestra]

06:42.694 --> 06:46.530
Where's that
marine lieutenant?
Lieutenant Cable!

06:48.116 --> 06:50.034
Yes?

06:50.118 --> 06:52.953
The captain wants to know
if you’d like to sit up
in the cockpit with him.

06:53.038 --> 06:55.039
Sure. Thanks.

06:57.626 --> 06:59.627
Ah, pull up a chair,
marine.

07:01.463 --> 07:03.631
I'm Buzz Adams.
Glad to know you.
Joe Cable.

07:03.715 --> 07:05.716
Nice to meet you, Joe.

07:09.763 --> 07:12.181
What are those islands
over there?

07:13.517 --> 07:16.852
[Buzz]
Japanese.
All of'em?

07:16.937 --> 07:18.938
Just a minute.

07:29.616 --> 07:33.911
[Explosions]

07:34.037 --> 07:37.581
Yeah, they're unfriendly.
Well, take it up!
What's the idea?

07:40.836 --> 07:43.963
It's all right.
I just wanted to show
the lieutenant.

07:44.047 --> 07:47.174
Thanks. I'll take
your word for it.

07:48.593 --> 07:50.970
You gotta do something
to break the monotony,
Lieutenant.

07:51.096 --> 07:54.723
If this war ever
really gets started—
It'll get started.

07:57.144 --> 07:59.645
Sure, sure,
it'll get started.

07:59.729 --> 08:01.730
Yeah.

08:03.817 --> 08:07.027
You, uh, ever hear of
a French civilian
down where we're going...

08:07.112 --> 08:09.530
named Emile De Becque?

08:10.574 --> 08:13.409
Yeah.

08:13.535 --> 08:16.871
What do you know about him?
Nobody knows much about him.

08:16.955 --> 08:21.584
He's rich, got a big
plantation on a hill,
hunts, fishes.

08:22.919 --> 08:24.837
What's he doing out here?

08:24.921 --> 08:29.758
Story goes that he had
to beat it out of France
some 15, 16 years ago.

08:29.843 --> 08:33.470
Nobody seems
to know much why.

08:33.554 --> 08:37.224
How 'bout taking me
on your mission
with you, Lieutenant?

08:38.602 --> 08:41.270
Who says I'm on
any mission?

08:42.688 --> 08:45.608
My mistake?
Your mistake.

08:48.028 --> 08:50.487
Sorry.

08:58.747 --> 09:01.582
Now, here we are.

09:08.840 --> 09:13.636
You see over there?
That's the fleet hospital
where they keep the nurses.

09:17.974 --> 09:19.725
That's where
the Seabees play.

09:19.935 --> 09:23.354
[Male Chorus]
♪ Bloody Mary is the girl I love. ♪

09:23.480 --> 09:27.233
♪ Bloody Mary is the girl I love. ♪
[Laughing]

09:27.317 --> 09:30.361
♪ Bloody Mary is the girl I love. ♪

09:30.445 --> 09:34.740
♪ Now ain't that too damn bad! ♪

09:34.824 --> 09:38.452
♪ Her skin is tender as a baseball glove. ♪

09:38.536 --> 09:42.164
♪ Her skin is tender
as a baseball glove. ♪

09:42.249 --> 09:45.167
♪ Her skin is tender as a baseball glove. ♪

09:45.252 --> 09:48.712
♪ Now ain't that too damn bad! ♪

09:49.923 --> 09:53.425
♪ Bloody Mary's chewing betel nuts, ♪

09:53.510 --> 09:57.179
♪ She is always chewing betel nuts, ♪

09:57.264 --> 10:00.224
♪ Bloody Mary's chewing betel nuts, ♪

10:00.308 --> 10:03.310
♪ And she don't use Pepsodent! ♪♪

10:11.236 --> 10:15.406
[Men Clapping, Whooping]

10:27.168 --> 10:30.504
[Men Hooting, Clapping]

10:37.929 --> 10:40.889
♪ Now ain't that ♪
Hey, Stewpot, Professor!

10:40.974 --> 10:45.227
♪ Too damn bad! ♪♪

10:46.479 --> 10:49.690
[Men Cheering]

10:52.610 --> 10:55.404
Here you are, Mary.
Put 'em down, Professor.

10:58.658 --> 11:00.659
These beautiful
grass skirts...

11:00.744 --> 11:05.289
were made by myself,
the Professor and Stewpot
and three other Seabees...

11:05.373 --> 11:08.834
in half the time
it takes your native workers
to make 'em.

11:08.918 --> 11:12.171
See? No stretch.

11:12.255 --> 11:16.133
Look 'em over, sweaty pie,
and give me a price.

11:18.428 --> 11:22.389
- All hand-tied.
- Now, what do you say, sweat-so.
What am I offered?

11:22.474 --> 11:25.017
Gee, pretty nice work.

11:25.101 --> 11:28.354
Did you hear that?
You can probably sell these
to the chumps...

11:28.438 --> 11:30.356
for five or six dollars apiece.

11:30.440 --> 11:35.277
Now, let's make a quick deal.
I'll let you have the whole
batch for say, um, 80 bucks.

11:35.403 --> 11:37.863
Give you 10 dollar.
What?

11:38.073 --> 11:40.199
[Men Chuckling]

11:40.283 --> 11:43.410
Aah! Now, see here,
dragon lady. You—

11:43.495 --> 11:46.121
Hey, what's that
you got there?

11:46.206 --> 11:48.332
A boar's tooth bracelet.

11:48.416 --> 11:52.086
Where'd you get that?
Over there on Bali Ha'i?

11:53.421 --> 11:55.422
You like?

11:56.758 --> 11:59.343
Hey, come here.
Come here.

12:00.970 --> 12:03.764
You don't run into
these things every day.

12:03.848 --> 12:06.350
They're scarce
as hen's teeth.

12:06.434 --> 12:08.852
They're bigger too.

12:08.937 --> 12:11.772
That darn Bali Ha'i.

12:16.653 --> 12:18.779
Why does it have to be
off-limits?

12:18.863 --> 12:20.864
You can get everything
over there—

12:20.949 --> 12:23.575
shrunken heads, bracelets.

12:23.660 --> 12:27.079
Only officers
can sign out boats.

12:27.163 --> 12:29.081
I'll get a boat,
all right.

12:29.165 --> 12:32.251
I'll latch on
to some officer who's
got some imagination,

12:32.335 --> 12:37.089
who would like to see that
boar's tooth ceremonial
as much as I would.

12:37.173 --> 12:40.384
It's a pip
of a ceremonial.

12:40.468 --> 12:43.929
Dancin', drinkin',

12:44.013 --> 12:46.014
everything.

12:48.143 --> 12:51.645
Why, you big phony.
We all know why you
wanna go to Bali Ha'i.

12:51.771 --> 12:54.106
Yeah? Why?
Because
the French planters...

12:54.190 --> 12:56.733
put their young women
over there when they heard
the G.I.'s were coming.

12:56.860 --> 13:00.487
That's why.
Just as if they
didn't trust us.

13:00.572 --> 13:05.826
The trouble with you is,
ain't boar's teeth.
It's women.

13:05.910 --> 13:08.495
It is boar's teeth...

13:08.580 --> 13:10.372
and women.

13:31.769 --> 13:35.647
♪ We got sunlight on the sand,
We got moonlight on the sea, ♪

13:35.732 --> 13:39.359
♪ We got mangoes and bananas
We can pick right off a tree, ♪

13:39.444 --> 13:43.572
♪ We got volley ball and ping pong
And a lot of dandy games. ♪

13:43.698 --> 13:49.328
♪ What ain't we got? ♪
♪ We ain't got dames. ♪

13:49.454 --> 13:53.582
♪ We get packages from home, ♪
♪ We get movies,
We get shows, ♪

13:53.666 --> 13:57.377
-♪ We get speeches from our skipper ♪
-♪ And advice from Tokyo Rose, ♪

13:57.462 --> 14:01.673
♪ We get letters doused wid poifume,
We get dizzy from de smell! ♪

14:01.799 --> 14:06.512
♪ What don't we get? ♪
♪ You know damn well! ♪

14:06.596 --> 14:12.267
♪ We got nothin'
to put on a clean
white suit for, ♪

14:12.352 --> 14:17.231
♪ What we need is what there
ain't no substitute for. ♪

14:17.315 --> 14:21.360
♪ There is nothin' like a dame, ♪

14:21.444 --> 14:25.239
♪ Nothin' in the world, ♪

14:25.323 --> 14:27.741
♪ There is nothin' you can name ♪

14:27.825 --> 14:33.247
♪ That is anythin' like a dame. ♪

14:33.331 --> 14:35.499
♪ We feel restless,
We feel blue, ♪

14:35.583 --> 14:37.501
♪ We feel lonely and, in brief♪

14:37.627 --> 14:41.088
♪ We feel ev'ry kind of feeling ♪
♪ but the feeling of relief. ♪

14:41.172 --> 14:45.175
♪ We feel hungry
as the wolf felt when
he met Red Riding Hood. ♪

14:45.301 --> 14:50.222
♪ What don't we feel? ♪
♪ We don't feel good! ♪

14:50.306 --> 14:55.561
♪ Lots of things in life are beautiful,
But brother, ♪

14:55.645 --> 15:00.023
♪ There is one particular thing
that is nothing whatsoever
in any way, shape or form ♪

15:00.108 --> 15:03.610
♪ like any other. ♪

15:03.695 --> 15:07.447
♪ There is nothin' like a dame, ♪

15:07.532 --> 15:11.577
♪ Nothin' in the world, ♪

15:11.661 --> 15:13.787
♪ There is nothin' you can name ♪

15:13.871 --> 15:18.041
♪ That is anythin' like a dame. ♪

15:18.126 --> 15:22.254
♪ Nothin' else is built the same! ♪

15:22.338 --> 15:26.675
♪ Nothin' in the world ♪

15:26.759 --> 15:29.094
♪ Has a soft and wavy frame ♪

15:29.178 --> 15:33.890
♪ like the silhouette of a dame. ♪

15:33.975 --> 15:39.187
[Deep Voice]
♪ There is absolutely nothin' ♪

15:39.272 --> 15:43.609
♪ like the frame ♪

15:43.693 --> 15:48.697
♪ of a dame. ♪

15:48.781 --> 15:52.326
[Women]
Hup, two, three, four.
Hup, two, three, four.

15:52.410 --> 15:55.287
Pick 'em up. Set 'em down.
Hup, two, three, four.

15:55.371 --> 15:57.497
Hup, two, three, four.

15:57.582 --> 16:00.125
Pick 'em up. Set 'em down.
Hup, two, three, four.

16:00.209 --> 16:05.213
Hup, two, three, four.
Hup, two, three, four.

16:05.298 --> 16:07.591
Hup, two, three, four.

16:09.135 --> 16:11.303
Hello.

16:11.387 --> 16:13.347
Luther.

16:13.431 --> 16:15.432
[Mockingly]
Luther.

16:22.065 --> 16:25.442
Yes, Miss Forbush.
Have you done
what you promised?

16:28.404 --> 16:30.405
Yes, Miss Forbush.

16:36.454 --> 16:38.455
I did it all last night.

16:38.539 --> 16:42.334
Uh, uh, you don't
have to open it now.

16:42.418 --> 16:44.336
Oh!

16:44.420 --> 16:47.381
Why, you do
beautiful work, Luther!

16:47.465 --> 16:53.136
Gosh, I guess I'm just
about the luckiest nurse on
this island to have found you.

16:53.221 --> 16:55.222
You're a treasure.

17:00.436 --> 17:02.938
Hup, two, three, four.

17:04.398 --> 17:07.401
♪♪ [All Whistling]

17:22.791 --> 17:27.295
She's a nice little girl.
But some of them nurses,
the officers can have 'em.

17:27.422 --> 17:30.966
They got 'em.
Well, they can have 'em.

17:31.050 --> 17:34.803
♪ So suppose a dame ain't bright,
Or completely free from flaws ♪

17:34.887 --> 17:38.473
♪ Or as faithful as a bird dog
or as kind as Santa Claus? ♪

17:38.558 --> 17:42.102
♪ It's a waste of time
to worry over things
that they have not. ♪

17:42.186 --> 17:44.146
♪ Be thankful for ♪

17:44.230 --> 17:46.398
♪ the things they've got! ♪

17:46.482 --> 17:49.860
Hup, two, three, four.
Hup, two, three, four.

17:49.944 --> 17:52.404
Hup, two, three, four.

17:52.488 --> 17:54.406
Hup, two, three, four.

17:54.490 --> 17:56.491
[Men]
♪ There is nothin' you can name ♪

17:56.576 --> 18:01.413
♪ That is anythin' like a dame ♪

18:01.497 --> 18:05.751
♪ There are no books like a dame ♪

18:05.835 --> 18:09.337
♪ And nothin' looks like a dame. ♪

18:09.422 --> 18:12.924
♪ There are no drinks like a dame, ♪

18:13.009 --> 18:16.678
♪ And nothin' thinks like a dame, ♪

18:16.763 --> 18:20.307
♪ Nothin' acts like a dame. ♪

18:20.391 --> 18:24.102
♪ Or attracts like a dame. ♪

18:24.187 --> 18:28.148
♪ There ain't a thing
that's wrong with
any man here ♪

18:28.232 --> 18:31.902
♪ That can't be cured
by puttin' him near ♪

18:31.986 --> 18:35.405
♪ A girly, womanly, female, ♪

18:35.490 --> 18:40.827
♪ feminine dame! ♪

18:44.207 --> 18:46.541
♪ There is nothin' you can name ♪

18:46.626 --> 18:50.045
♪ that is anythin' ♪♪

18:51.964 --> 18:53.965
Hello.

19:16.572 --> 19:19.032
You make trouble for me?

19:19.116 --> 19:20.742
Huh?

19:22.787 --> 19:25.038
Are you crummy major?

19:26.123 --> 19:28.583
No, I'm even crummier
than that.

19:28.668 --> 19:30.585
I'm a lieutenant.

19:31.754 --> 19:33.755
"Lootellan."

19:34.799 --> 19:36.758
Lootellan.

19:41.889 --> 19:44.516
Hiya, Lootellan.
New on the rock?

19:44.600 --> 19:46.601
Just flew in
on that P.B.Y.

19:46.686 --> 19:50.564
- Where from?
- Little island south of Marie Louise.

19:50.648 --> 19:52.315
Hey, Lootellan.

20:04.412 --> 20:06.997
You sexy man.

20:07.081 --> 20:09.624
[Men Laughing]

20:09.709 --> 20:14.713
Thanks. Uh, you're
looking pretty, uh,
fit yourself.

20:14.839 --> 20:18.466
[All Laughing]
Sexy!

20:22.972 --> 20:25.223
Who's she?
Ah, nobody.

20:25.308 --> 20:27.309
She's Tonkinese.

20:31.314 --> 20:33.398
You got sweetheart?

20:33.482 --> 20:35.692
Take home Chicago
to sexy sweetheart.

20:35.776 --> 20:40.238
Oh, no, she's a Philadelphia girl.
I doubt that she'd quite appreciate.

20:40.323 --> 20:43.283
What's that
"Philadelia" girl?

20:43.409 --> 20:47.662
What's that mean?
No sexy?
[All Laughing]

20:47.747 --> 20:49.873
You like,
I give you free.

20:49.957 --> 20:52.626
Free? You never give me
anything free.

20:52.710 --> 20:54.794
You no sexy
like Lootellan.

20:54.879 --> 20:58.840
[All Laughing]

20:59.008 --> 21:01.051
Take.

21:01.135 --> 21:04.346
No, thanks.
Where'd you get that anyway?

21:07.016 --> 21:09.017
Bali Ha'i.

21:14.065 --> 21:17.692
[Female Chorus]
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪

21:20.947 --> 21:26.409
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪

21:27.703 --> 21:32.040
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪

21:36.712 --> 21:41.508
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪♪

21:41.634 --> 21:45.178
There's your officer.
[Whispering]
Leave it to me.

21:47.056 --> 21:49.432
Intriguin' little island,
ain't it, Lieutenant?

21:50.893 --> 21:54.604
Officers can get launches
and go over there.

21:57.441 --> 22:01.069
Bali Ha'i.
What's that mean?

22:03.072 --> 22:07.742
Bali Ha'i mean
"I am your special island."

22:08.995 --> 22:11.746
Mean "Here I am."

22:11.831 --> 22:15.375
Bali Ha'i your special
island, Lootellan.

22:15.459 --> 22:17.377
I know.

22:17.461 --> 22:20.922
You listen.
You hear island
call to you.

22:21.007 --> 22:24.259
Listen.
You no hear something?

22:43.529 --> 22:46.573
You hear voice?

22:46.657 --> 22:48.992
♪ Mos' people live ♪

22:49.076 --> 22:55.290
♪ on a lonely island ♪

22:56.375 --> 22:58.376
♪ Lost in de middle ♪

22:58.461 --> 23:04.340
♪ of a foggy sea ♪

23:05.509 --> 23:07.719
♪ Mos' people long ♪

23:07.803 --> 23:14.392
♪ for a nudder island ♪

23:14.477 --> 23:17.270
♪ One where dey know ♪

23:17.354 --> 23:24.819
♪ dey would like to be ♪

23:25.946 --> 23:31.493
♪ Bali Ha'i may call you ♪

23:31.577 --> 23:36.456
♪ Any night,
any day ♪

23:36.540 --> 23:41.169
♪ In your heart
You'll hear it call you ♪

23:41.253 --> 23:45.757
♪ "Come away, come away." ♪

23:45.841 --> 23:51.096
♪ Bali Ha'i will whisper ♪

23:51.180 --> 23:55.600
♪ On de wind of de sea; ♪

23:55.684 --> 24:00.605
♪ "Here am I,
Your special island!" ♪

24:00.689 --> 24:05.443
♪ "Come to me, come to me!" ♪

24:05.528 --> 24:09.989
♪ Your own special hopes, ♪

24:10.074 --> 24:15.203
♪ Your own special dreams ♪

24:15.287 --> 24:19.290
♪ Bloom on de hillside ♪

24:19.375 --> 24:25.088
♪ And shine
in de streams. ♪

24:25.172 --> 24:28.091
♪ If you try, ♪

24:28.175 --> 24:30.135
♪ You'll find me ♪

24:30.219 --> 24:35.098
♪ Where de sky
meets de sea, ♪

24:35.182 --> 24:40.061
♪ "Here am I,
Your special island!" ♪

24:40.146 --> 24:44.315
♪ "Come to me.
Come to me!" ♪

24:44.400 --> 24:47.527
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪

24:47.611 --> 24:50.155
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪

24:50.239 --> 24:56.411
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪

24:56.495 --> 25:00.748
♪ Someday you'll see me, ♪

25:00.833 --> 25:04.919
♪ Floatin' in de sunshine, ♪

25:05.004 --> 25:08.381
♪ My head stickin' out ♪

25:08.465 --> 25:12.010
♪ F'um a low flyin' cloud. ♪

25:14.597 --> 25:18.683
♪ You'll hear me
call you, ♪

25:18.767 --> 25:23.771
♪ Singin' through
the sunshine, ♪

25:23.856 --> 25:28.193
♪ Sweet and clear ♪

25:28.277 --> 25:32.947
♪ as can be, ♪

25:34.950 --> 25:37.619
♪ "Come to me, ♪

25:37.703 --> 25:39.996
♪ Here am I, ♪

25:40.080 --> 25:45.668
♪ Come to me!" ♪

25:45.753 --> 25:51.216
♪ If you try
you'll find me ♪

25:51.300 --> 25:55.511
♪ Where de sky
meets de sea ♪

25:55.596 --> 26:00.975
♪ Hear am I,
Your special island ♪

26:01.060 --> 26:03.061
♪ Come to me ♪

26:04.230 --> 26:06.814
♪ Come to me ♪

26:06.899 --> 26:09.984
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪

26:10.069 --> 26:14.155
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪

26:14.240 --> 26:22.997
♪ Bali Ha'i ♪♪

26:45.562 --> 26:47.897
Of course, Lieutenant,
uh, right now,

26:47.982 --> 26:51.734
uh, that island
is off-limits.

26:53.028 --> 26:55.446
Of course,
you being an officer,

26:55.531 --> 26:57.699
you could get a launch.

26:57.783 --> 26:59.742
I'd even be willin'...

26:59.827 --> 27:02.829
to requisition
a boat for you.

27:05.040 --> 27:08.626
[Chuckles]
But another thing
goes on over there.

27:08.711 --> 27:14.340
The, uh, ceremonial
of the boar's tooth.

27:14.425 --> 27:16.426
After they kill the boar,

27:16.510 --> 27:21.306
they... pass around
some of that, uh,

27:21.390 --> 27:24.017
coconut liquor.

27:24.101 --> 27:27.937
And women, uh, dance
with just skirts on.

27:30.065 --> 27:34.861
And everybody gets
to know everybody
pretty well.

27:34.945 --> 27:37.488
And I thought you bein'
up in the shootin' war...

27:37.573 --> 27:40.992
for such a long time
without getting any recreation,

27:41.076 --> 27:45.246
uh, thought you might
be interested.

27:45.331 --> 27:47.957
[Whooping]
Iron belly.

27:48.042 --> 27:51.336
[Men Whooping]

27:51.420 --> 27:54.088
[Whooping Continues]

27:59.261 --> 28:01.262
Here she is, sir.

28:06.477 --> 28:09.896
You are causing
an economic revolution
on this island.

28:09.980 --> 28:13.858
These French planters
can't find a native
to pick a coconut...

28:13.942 --> 28:15.860
or milk a cow...

28:15.944 --> 28:18.363
because you're paying them
10 times as much...

28:18.447 --> 28:21.908
to make these ridiculous
grass skirts.

28:21.992 --> 28:24.660
French planters
stingy stinker!

28:24.745 --> 28:26.746
Like you,
crummy Captain!

28:32.753 --> 28:37.507
I want you to pick up
every scrap of this
paraphernalia now.

28:37.591 --> 28:41.219
And for the last time,
carry it way down there...

28:41.303 --> 28:43.388
beyond that pier...

28:43.472 --> 28:46.724
off navy property.

28:57.403 --> 29:00.947
All right, you men!
Take this stuff down there
past that pier!

29:01.031 --> 29:03.032
Snap to it!

29:05.661 --> 29:07.995
Who is he?
Don't know, sir.

29:08.080 --> 29:10.957
All right, all right.
Come on. Let's go.

29:11.041 --> 29:14.460
Get it down there.
Let's go. Let's go.
Come on. Come on.

29:14.545 --> 29:18.840
Way down there.
Off navy property.

29:20.801 --> 29:22.718
You go too.

29:22.803 --> 29:25.263
All right, Lootellan.

29:25.347 --> 29:27.348
Thank you.

29:29.977 --> 29:32.353
Lieutenant?
Who are you anyway?

29:32.438 --> 29:36.149
Lieutenant Joseph Cable, sir.
I just flew in
on that P.B.Y.

29:36.275 --> 29:38.359
A joyride?
No, sir. Orders.

29:38.485 --> 29:42.113
A marine under orders
to me?
Yes, sir.

29:42.197 --> 29:44.657
This is Commander Harbison,
my executive officer.

29:44.783 --> 29:47.285
Commander.
Lieutenant Cable.

29:47.369 --> 29:49.620
Well, what's it
all about?

29:49.705 --> 29:51.789
Well, sir,

29:51.874 --> 29:54.208
my colonel feels...

29:54.293 --> 29:56.294
that all these islands
are in danger...

29:56.378 --> 30:00.548
because none of us
has been getting any
firsthand intelligence.

30:00.632 --> 30:03.009
We don't know
what the Japanese
are really up to.

30:03.093 --> 30:05.052
He couldn't be more right.

30:05.179 --> 30:08.222
He feels that what
we need is a coast watch.
A coast watch?

30:08.307 --> 30:11.476
Yes, sir.
One of our men
with a radio...

30:11.560 --> 30:14.645
hiding out on one
of the enemy-held islands...

30:14.730 --> 30:16.898
where he could watch
for enemy ships...

30:16.982 --> 30:20.902
when they come down
through the bottleneck
down this way.

30:20.986 --> 30:23.821
What do you think,
Bill?

30:23.906 --> 30:26.699
Well, sir, our pilots
could do a lot of damage...

30:26.783 --> 30:30.244
to enemy convoys with
information like that.

30:30.329 --> 30:32.830
How would you get a man
on one of those islands?

30:32.915 --> 30:35.666
Have to sneak him ashore
somehow, sir.

30:35.751 --> 30:38.669
How long do you think
he could hold out there
sending messages...

30:38.754 --> 30:40.755
before the Japanese
spotted him?

30:40.839 --> 30:42.757
It could be done, sir.

30:42.841 --> 30:45.301
Yeah, but who's
going to do it?

30:45.385 --> 30:49.096
Well, sir,
I've been elected.

30:49.181 --> 30:52.308
You got yourself
quite an assignment, son.

30:54.144 --> 30:56.062
I think I'd be okay...

30:56.146 --> 30:59.482
if I could take a man
with me who really
knew the country.

30:59.566 --> 31:02.818
Headquarters has found out
that there's a French
civilian here...

31:02.903 --> 31:05.571
used to have a plantation
on Marie Louise Island.

31:05.656 --> 31:08.449
Did a lot of hunting
and fishing there.

31:08.534 --> 31:12.828
Marie Louise.
That's a good spot.
Right on the bottleneck.

31:12.955 --> 31:15.540
What's this
Frenchman's name?
Emile De Becque.

31:15.624 --> 31:19.043
Ah! He lives
right up there.

31:19.169 --> 31:23.214
[Cable]
Yes, sir. Do you know him?
Well, I've met him.

31:23.298 --> 31:26.926
But I don't know
very much about him... yet.

31:33.725 --> 31:35.810
Is all this yours?
Yes.

31:35.894 --> 31:40.273
[Miss Forbush]
Is it true that all the planters
on these islands—

31:40.357 --> 31:42.984
Are they really running away
from something?

31:44.528 --> 31:49.740
Uh, who is not running away
from something?

31:49.825 --> 31:51.993
There are fugitives
everywhere.

31:52.077 --> 31:54.412
New York, in Paris,

31:54.496 --> 31:57.081
even in Small Rock.

31:57.165 --> 31:59.166
Yeah, where you come from.

31:59.251 --> 32:01.335
Oh! Little Rock.

32:01.420 --> 32:04.297
Oh, Little. Oh.
[Chuckles]
Yes.

32:04.423 --> 32:06.799
Small Rock.
Excuse me. Little Rock.

32:06.883 --> 32:09.552
You know
any fugitives there?

32:09.636 --> 32:12.597
I'll show you a picture
of a Little Rock fugitive.

32:15.934 --> 32:19.562
I got this clipping
from my mother... today.

32:21.231 --> 32:23.941
Hey.
[Chuckles]

32:24.026 --> 32:26.777
"Ensign Nellie Forbush,

32:26.862 --> 32:30.364
Arkansas's own
Florence Nightingale."

32:30.449 --> 32:32.617
That was written
by Mrs. Leeming,
the social editor.

32:32.743 --> 32:34.952
Hmm.
She went to school
with my mother.

32:35.037 --> 32:38.039
Pretty girl, huh?

32:38.123 --> 32:41.459
That picture was taken
before I knew what...

32:41.543 --> 32:45.504
rain and heat and mud
can do to your disposition.

32:47.007 --> 32:49.258
[Sighs]

32:49.343 --> 32:51.677
But it isn't
raining today.

32:53.722 --> 32:56.724
Gosh, it's beautiful here.

32:56.808 --> 33:00.144
Just look
at that yellow sun.

33:00.228 --> 33:03.731
And way off in the distance,
those lovely little
white clouds.

33:03.815 --> 33:08.069
Those lovely little
white clouds could
easily be gunfire.

33:10.489 --> 33:12.490
Oh, how awful.

33:13.825 --> 33:16.410
On such a day.

33:16.495 --> 33:19.246
Boys getting killed,
people getting—

33:22.125 --> 33:26.295
But you know, Emile, I don't
think it's the end of the world
like everyone else thinks.

33:26.421 --> 33:29.548
Do you?
Perhaps the end
of some worlds.

33:29.633 --> 33:32.009
Not this one.

33:32.094 --> 33:34.512
It can't be.

33:34.596 --> 33:38.766
I— I can't work myself up
to getting that low.

33:40.852 --> 33:44.980
You think I'm crazy too?
They all do over
at the fleet hospital.

33:45.065 --> 33:48.693
You know what they call me?
Knucklehead Nellie.

33:50.779 --> 33:52.905
I suppose I am.

33:52.989 --> 33:55.950
But I can't help it.

33:56.118 --> 34:02.206
♪ When the sky is
a bright canary yellow ♪

34:02.290 --> 34:06.377
♪ I forget ev'ry cloud
I've ever seen ♪

34:06.461 --> 34:11.257
♪ So they call me
a cockeyed optimist, ♪

34:11.341 --> 34:15.678
♪ Immature
and incurably green! ♪

34:15.762 --> 34:20.391
♪ I have heard people
rant and rave and bellow ♪

34:20.475 --> 34:25.062
♪ That we're done
and we might as well be dead ♪

34:25.147 --> 34:29.315
♪ But I'm only
a cockeyed optimist ♪

34:29.400 --> 34:34.237
♪ And I can't get it
into my head, ♪

34:34.322 --> 34:39.076
♪ I hear the human race
is falling on its face ♪

34:39.161 --> 34:45.081
♪ And hasn't very far to go, ♪

34:45.167 --> 34:49.545
♪ But ev'ry whippoorwill
Is selling me a bill ♪

34:49.629 --> 34:53.549
♪ And telling me
it just ain't so. ♪

34:53.632 --> 34:59.263
♪ I could say life is just
a bowl of jello, ♪

34:59.347 --> 35:03.934
♪ And appear more intelligent
and smart ♪

35:04.019 --> 35:08.606
♪ But I'm stuck (like a dope!)
With a thing called hope, ♪

35:08.690 --> 35:13.861
♪ And I can't get it
out of my heart ♪

35:13.945 --> 35:16.614
♪ Not ♪

35:16.698 --> 35:18.824
♪ this ♪

35:18.909 --> 35:27.750
♪ heart. ♪♪

35:30.212 --> 35:33.297
Do you wanna know
anything else about me?

35:33.381 --> 35:35.591
Yes.

35:35.717 --> 35:38.469
Would you like
to see the view?
Mmm.

35:42.057 --> 35:45.684
You say you are
a fugitive.

35:45.769 --> 35:49.688
When you joined the navy,
what were you running
away from?

35:51.107 --> 35:53.776
Gosh, I don't know.

35:53.860 --> 35:56.445
It was more like
running to something.

35:56.530 --> 35:59.740
I wanted to see
what the world was like—
outside of Little Rock, I mean.

35:59.825 --> 36:02.243
And I wanted to meet
different kinds of people...

36:02.327 --> 36:04.787
and find out if I liked 'em better.

36:04.871 --> 36:06.997
And do you?

36:08.792 --> 36:10.835
Well, I-I don't
really know yet.

36:10.919 --> 36:14.630
I guess they're...
different.

36:16.466 --> 36:20.261
Would you like some cognac?
I'd love some.

36:27.644 --> 36:30.855
[Nellie's Voice]
♪ Wonder how I'd feel ♪

36:30.939 --> 36:33.732
♪ Living on a hillside, ♪

36:33.817 --> 36:36.694
♪ Looking on an ocean, ♪

36:36.778 --> 36:40.114
♪ Beautiful and still. ♪

36:42.742 --> 36:45.703
[Emile's Voice]
♪ This is what I need, ♪

36:45.787 --> 36:48.622
♪ This is what
I've longed for, ♪

36:48.707 --> 36:51.792
♪ Someone young and smiling ♪

36:51.877 --> 36:57.882
♪ Climbing up my hill! ♪

36:57.966 --> 37:01.093
[Nellie's Voice]
♪ We are not alike. ♪

37:01.177 --> 37:04.138
♪ Probably I'd bore him. ♪

37:04.222 --> 37:07.182
♪ He's a cultured Frenchman, ♪

37:07.267 --> 37:09.894
♪ I'm a little hick. ♪

37:13.481 --> 37:16.108
[Emile's Voice]
♪ Younger men than I, ♪

37:16.192 --> 37:19.153
♪ Officers and doctors, ♪

37:19.237 --> 37:22.281
♪ Probably pursue her, ♪

37:22.365 --> 37:25.492
♪ She could have her pick. ♪

37:28.204 --> 37:30.372
[Nellie's Voice]
♪ Wonder why I feel ♪

37:30.457 --> 37:32.625
♪Jittery and jumpy! ♪

37:32.709 --> 37:35.294
♪ I am like a school-girl, ♪

37:35.378 --> 37:38.464
♪ Waiting for a dance. ♪

37:38.548 --> 37:40.799
[Emile's Voice]
♪ Can I ask her now? ♪

37:40.884 --> 37:43.218
♪ I am like a school boy! ♪

37:43.303 --> 37:47.139
♪ What will be her answer? ♪

37:47.223 --> 37:50.893
♪ Do I have ♪

37:50.977 --> 37:55.397
♪ a chance? ♪♪

38:52.747 --> 38:54.832
In peacetime,

38:54.916 --> 38:57.668
the boat from America
comes once a month.

38:57.752 --> 38:59.753
The ladies—

39:01.131 --> 39:03.340
the wives
of the planters—

39:03.425 --> 39:06.593
often go to Australia
during the hot months.

39:08.054 --> 39:09.930
It can get
very hot here.

39:10.056 --> 39:13.267
Oh, it can get hot
in Arkansas too.
It can?

39:13.351 --> 39:15.352
Uh-huh.

39:19.858 --> 39:22.860
I have many books here.

39:22.944 --> 39:24.945
Marcel Proust?

39:27.866 --> 39:29.867
Anatole France?

39:31.619 --> 39:34.121
Did you study French
in school?

39:34.205 --> 39:36.206
Oh, yes.

39:36.291 --> 39:38.292
Then you can read French.

39:39.669 --> 39:42.337
No.

39:42.422 --> 39:45.424
I can conjugate
a few verbs.

39:48.970 --> 39:52.056
I'll bet you read a lot.

39:52.140 --> 39:56.351
Out here, one becomes hungry
to learn everything.

39:56.436 --> 40:00.898
Not to miss anything.
Not to let anything good
pass by.

40:02.817 --> 40:05.652
[Sets Glass Down]

40:14.621 --> 40:16.538
Yes?

40:18.416 --> 40:21.794
One waits so long
for what is good,

40:21.878 --> 40:24.838
and when at last it comes,

40:24.923 --> 40:28.258
one cannot risk to lose.

40:28.343 --> 40:30.719
So one must speak
and act quickly,

40:30.804 --> 40:33.889
even if it seems
almost foolish
to be so quick.

40:33.973 --> 40:38.352
I know it's only two weeks.
A dinner given at your
Officers Club, wasn't it?

40:38.436 --> 40:40.437
Yes, it was, Emile.

40:40.522 --> 40:43.774
And that is the way
things happen sometimes.

40:43.900 --> 40:46.735
Isn't it, Nellie?
Yes, it is, Emile.

40:47.862 --> 40:52.491
♪ Some enchanted evening ♪

40:53.535 --> 40:58.330
♪ You may see a stranger, ♪

40:58.414 --> 41:01.834
♪ You may see
a stranger ♪

41:01.918 --> 41:06.713
♪ Across a crowded room ♪

41:06.798 --> 41:10.801
♪ And somehow you know, ♪

41:11.803 --> 41:16.682
♪ You know even then ♪

41:16.766 --> 41:20.602
♪ That somewhere
you'll see her ♪

41:20.687 --> 41:26.066
♪ again and again. ♪

41:28.486 --> 41:33.574
♪ Some enchanted evening ♪

41:33.658 --> 41:38.662
♪ Someone may be laughing, ♪

41:38.746 --> 41:42.207
♪ You may hear her laughing, ♪

41:42.292 --> 41:46.420
♪ Across a crowded room ♪

41:47.755 --> 41:52.050
♪ And night after night, ♪

41:53.052 --> 41:57.973
♪ As strange as it seems ♪

41:58.057 --> 42:02.019
♪ The sound of her laughter ♪

42:02.103 --> 42:08.567
♪ will sing in your dreams. ♪

42:11.321 --> 42:14.573
♪ Who can explain it? ♪

42:14.657 --> 42:18.035
♪ Who can tell you why? ♪

42:18.119 --> 42:22.080
♪ Fools give you reasons, ♪

42:22.165 --> 42:30.214
♪ Wise men never try. ♪

42:30.298 --> 42:34.468
♪ Some enchanted evening ♪

42:35.595 --> 42:40.641
♪ When you find
your true love, ♪

42:40.725 --> 42:44.394
♪ When you feel her
call you ♪

42:44.479 --> 42:49.524
♪ Across a crowded room, ♪

42:49.609 --> 42:54.863
♪ Then fly to her side ♪

42:54.948 --> 43:00.494
♪ And make her your own, ♪

43:00.578 --> 43:04.081
♪ Or all through
your life ♪

43:04.165 --> 43:07.542
♪ you may dream ♪

43:07.627 --> 43:09.544
♪ all ♪

43:09.629 --> 43:15.509
♪ alone. ♪

43:18.346 --> 43:22.557
♪ Once you have
found her, ♪

43:22.642 --> 43:26.144
♪ Never let her go. ♪

43:27.188 --> 43:32.234
♪ Once you have
found her, ♪

43:33.236 --> 43:36.029
♪ Never ♪

43:36.114 --> 43:38.198
♪ let ♪

43:38.283 --> 43:41.368
♪ her ♪

43:41.452 --> 43:47.791
♪ go! ♪♪

43:59.721 --> 44:02.639
I am older than you.

44:02.724 --> 44:05.559
If we have children,

44:05.643 --> 44:07.811
when I die,

44:07.895 --> 44:10.689
they will be growing up.

44:10.773 --> 44:14.026
You could afford
to take them back
to America,

44:14.110 --> 44:16.111
if you like.

44:23.369 --> 44:25.370
Think about it.

44:29.792 --> 44:33.253
Monsieur De Becque.
[Speaking French]

44:33.338 --> 44:36.298
[French Continues]

44:40.345 --> 44:43.764
Oh! Oh, my jeep.

44:45.516 --> 44:48.602
Thanks, Henry.
Tell 'em I'll be right there.

44:50.897 --> 44:53.357
Good-bye, Emile.
I had such a lovely time. I—

44:53.441 --> 44:57.277
Before you leave, Nellie,
I want to tell you
something.

44:57.362 --> 45:01.114
A while ago
you asked me a question:
Why did I leave France?

45:01.240 --> 45:03.283
Emile, that was nothing—
But I want to tell you.

45:04.660 --> 45:08.663
I had to leave France.
I killed a man.

45:08.748 --> 45:11.583
Why did you kill him?

45:12.794 --> 45:15.045
He was a wicked man—

45:15.129 --> 45:17.255
the town bully.

45:17.340 --> 45:20.258
Everyone in our village
was glad to see him die.

45:20.343 --> 45:22.302
And it was not
to my discredit.

45:23.596 --> 45:25.597
Do you believe me,
Nellie?

45:28.393 --> 45:31.436
You— You just told me
that you killed a man...

45:31.521 --> 45:33.522
and that it's all right.

45:36.692 --> 45:38.693
I hardly know you.

45:39.987 --> 45:41.988
And yet I know
it's all right.

45:42.073 --> 45:44.074
Thank you, Nellie.

45:45.743 --> 45:48.745
And you like my place?

45:50.081 --> 45:53.875
Yes.
You— You will think?

45:56.963 --> 45:58.964
I will think.

46:11.519 --> 46:13.520
Shh.

46:32.748 --> 46:36.376
♪ La, da-da, da-da, da ♪

46:36.461 --> 46:38.920
[Children]
♪ La, la-la, la-la, la ♪

46:39.005 --> 46:41.548
Oh.
[Chuckles,
Speaks French]

46:41.632 --> 46:45.760
[All Speaking French]

46:53.769 --> 46:56.188
♪ Dites-moi ♪

46:56.272 --> 46:58.273
♪ pour quoi ♪

46:58.357 --> 47:01.318
♪ La vie est belle ♪

47:01.402 --> 47:04.279
[All]
♪ Dites-moi ♪

47:04.363 --> 47:06.156
♪ pour quoi ♪

47:06.240 --> 47:09.743
♪ La vie est gaie? ♪

47:09.827 --> 47:12.287
♪ Dites-moi ♪

47:12.371 --> 47:14.247
♪ pour quoi ♪

47:14.332 --> 47:18.835
♪ Chere mad'moiseille ♪

47:18.920 --> 47:20.837
♪ Est ce que ♪

47:20.922 --> 47:23.006
♪ Par ce que ♪

47:23.090 --> 47:25.884
♪ vous m'aimez ♪♪

47:38.439 --> 47:40.440
I'm Lieutenant Cable.

47:43.444 --> 47:47.572
[Brackett]
Oh, come in, Cable.
Come over here.

47:47.657 --> 47:52.035
Look at this.
We've got some dope
on your Frenchman.

47:52.119 --> 47:54.538
Had a plantation
on Marie Louise Island.

47:54.622 --> 47:57.916
Moved down here
to this island
16 years ago.

47:58.000 --> 48:00.752
Married to a Polynesian
woman for about five years.

48:00.836 --> 48:04.965
Two children by her.
She died.

48:05.049 --> 48:07.300
Here's one thing
we've got to clear up.

48:07.385 --> 48:09.761
Seems he left France
in a hurry.

48:09.845 --> 48:14.349
Killed a guy.
What do you think of that?

48:14.475 --> 48:18.436
Might be a handy man
to have around.
[Intercom Buzzes]

48:18.521 --> 48:20.438
Cable.

48:20.523 --> 48:22.482
Good. Send her in.

48:22.567 --> 48:26.111
Here she is.
Oh, come in, Miss Forbush.

48:29.407 --> 48:31.866
Captain Brackett,
please excuse the way I look.

48:31.993 --> 48:33.952
I was just—
Oh, you look fine.

48:34.036 --> 48:36.663
May I present
Commander Harbison?

48:36.747 --> 48:39.833
I have the pleasure
of meeting Miss Forbush
twice a week.

48:41.794 --> 48:45.213
We serve together
on the G.I.
entertainment committee.

48:45.339 --> 48:48.466
Oh.
How's the Thanksgiving
entertainment coming along?

48:48.551 --> 48:52.429
Very well. Thank you, sir.
We practice whenever
we get a chance.

48:52.513 --> 48:57.100
May I also present
Lieutenant Joseph Cable?
Miss Forbush.

48:57.184 --> 48:59.686
Sit down, Miss Forbush.

49:07.820 --> 49:11.072
Miss Forbush, you've been
seeing a French planter,
Emile De Becque.

49:12.366 --> 49:14.284
Yes, sir.

49:14.368 --> 49:17.037
Good. What do you know
about him?

49:19.373 --> 49:23.460
Well, uh, uh,
what do I know about him?

49:23.544 --> 49:26.004
That's right.

49:27.340 --> 49:29.341
Well, I, uh—

49:31.636 --> 49:34.971
We met at
the Officers Club dance.

49:35.056 --> 49:38.892
He was there.
And I met him.

49:38.976 --> 49:41.728
Yes. Now, what kind
of a man is he?

49:43.648 --> 49:45.649
Well, uh,

49:47.026 --> 49:49.027
he's very nice.

49:50.404 --> 49:52.405
He's kind.

49:53.741 --> 49:55.659
He's attractive.

49:59.080 --> 50:01.331
I just don't know
what you wanna know, sir.

50:01.415 --> 50:05.043
Miss Forbush,
Captain Brackett
wants to know,

50:05.127 --> 50:07.045
did you discuss
politics?

50:07.129 --> 50:08.797
No, sir.

50:10.633 --> 50:13.885
Would you have discussed
politics, Commander?

50:15.429 --> 50:18.098
What we're specifically
interested in is—

50:18.182 --> 50:22.394
well, when these fellas come
out from France, it's generally
because they've had trouble.

50:22.478 --> 50:24.479
Has he ever told you
anything about that?

50:33.531 --> 50:36.241
Well, uh, what do you know
about his family, for instance?

50:36.325 --> 50:39.160
Oh, uh, he has no family.

50:39.245 --> 50:41.621
No wife. Nobody.

50:43.666 --> 50:46.543
- He doesn't have any children?
- No, sir.

50:46.627 --> 50:50.130
And you say
he's never told you
why he left France?

50:52.299 --> 50:54.884
Yes, sir.

50:54.969 --> 50:57.137
He left France
because he killed a man.

50:59.807 --> 51:01.725
Did he tell you why?

51:01.809 --> 51:05.061
No, but he will
if I ask him.

51:05.146 --> 51:08.231
Well, Miss Forbush,
that's exactly what
we'd like to have you do.

51:08.315 --> 51:11.317
Find out as much
about him as you can—

51:11.402 --> 51:15.655
his background, his opinions
and why he killed
this man in France.

51:15.740 --> 51:18.950
In other words,
you want me to spy on him?

51:20.494 --> 51:23.079
Well, I'm afraid it is
something like that.

51:23.164 --> 51:26.082
Why? Do you suspect
him of anything?

51:26.167 --> 51:29.919
No. It's just
that we don't know
very much about him.

51:30.004 --> 51:33.506
And he's— Will you
help us, Miss Forbush?

51:35.342 --> 51:37.260
I'll try.

51:37.344 --> 51:40.847
Thank you. You may
go now if you wish.

51:40.931 --> 51:42.932
Thank you.

51:48.689 --> 51:52.192
I don't know very much
about him, really.

51:52.276 --> 51:54.277
Do I?

52:05.039 --> 52:07.791
He's kept a few secrets
from her, hasn't he?

52:07.875 --> 52:12.545
Well, you don't spring a couple
of Polynesian kids on a woman
right off the bat.

52:12.630 --> 52:15.507
I'm afraid
we aren't gonna get
much out of her.

52:15.591 --> 52:17.801
She's obviously
in love with him.

52:17.885 --> 52:22.347
That's hard to believe, sir.
They tell me he's
a middle-aged man.

52:22.431 --> 52:25.099
Cable,

52:25.184 --> 52:28.978
it is a common mistake
for boys of your age...

52:29.063 --> 52:31.064
and athletic ability...

52:31.148 --> 52:34.692
to underestimate men
who have reached
their maturity.

52:34.819 --> 52:39.906
Sir, I didn't mean—
Young women frequently find
a grown man attractive,

